Your code calls [`getIterator()`][1], which will prevent any database magic from ever happening, because it initializes the collection (which loads all entries), so your collation doesn&#39;t matter anyway.

Also, the [`contains`][2] function uses `strpos`, which obviously is not case-insensitive.

Since your code already pulls in all hashtags, just filter it already:

    $hashtags = array_filter(function(Hashtag $hashtag) {
        return stripos($this-&gt;name, $hashtag-&gt;getName());
    }, $this-&gt;hashtags);
    if(!empty($max)) {
        $hashtags = array_slice($hashtags, 0, $max, true); 
        // remove true, if you don&#39;t care about keys  ^, this preserves them
    }
    return $hashtags;

  [1]: http://I%20would%20assume,%20that%20%60$hashtags-%3EgetIterator()%60%20will%20prevent%20any%20database%20magic%20from%20ever%20happening,%20because%20it%20initializes%20the%20collection(see:%20https://github.com/doctrine/collections/blob/7e6599ffdc7287f6732e05af534f873a971a554d/lib/Doctrine/Common/Collections/AbstractLazyCollection.php#L281)
  [2]: https://github.com/doctrine/collections/blob/7e6599ffdc7287f6732e05af534f873a971a554d/lib/Doctrine/Common/Collections/Expr/ClosureExpressionVisitor.php#L156

